<Name>Keith Paulsen<//Name>< review>
Glad we found this restaurant open for inside dining. We didn't arrive until after 8:15 and we were ready for a good meal.
They serve family style with bread, salad, a dish of garbanzo beans, and delicious minestrone soup. We added the garbanzo beans to soup and made it even more delicious.
The ribeye steak had an incredible flavor. I was too full to finish my baked potato. The owner was very nice and the staff was great! I will definitely return next time I'm near Alturas.</review>

1592073471526<//date>
<Rating>2< /Rating>< Review>
We have going to the Brass Rail for dinner for decades.  We lived in Alturas and in Likely for many years and it was always a treat to have dinner there till last. Night.  The service was very good and all of the food brought out was excellent till the main course.  We ordered 3 Rib steaks .  when they came they looked huge and poorly cut.  They were seasoned well and cooked correctly but they were so full of gristle we could not cut through them....let alone even begin to chew through that awful gristle.  The waitress was very nice and offered to cook new steaks but we were travelling and had no way to heat them etc.  We declined and asked that the chef please cut into them to see how truly they could not be eaten.  We had hoped they would comp at least INE dinner but there was no offer made.  We were extremely disappointed...especially when one of our party travelled 2 days to get there.  I don't know what has happened but the original owners would never have run the restaurant like this.< /Review>

We made it a point to stop here on a Sunday at noon to try Basque food. The Basque part of the restaurant, but all that is open for lunch is the pub. Great food, great bar,  and great people!< /Review>
<Pics>None<//Pics><Response>None<//Response>< GmapID>
0x54cb85d6a549b93b:0xd5c44360bd54363c< /GmapID>
</record></dataset><record>
<text>We walked into the quaint little bar, which gave us a good feeling. Then we passed through the curtain of beads separating us from the restaurant, and taking in the quality of the furnishings we began to fear for the longevity of our bank accounts and briefly considered whether we shouldn't sneak out the back door before anybody noticed us, at which point someone of course DID notice us and showed us to our seat. Our server disappeared into the back, prompting us to again ponder if it wouldn't be prudent to make a crazed dash for the front door like the building was on fire before she came back, at which point she of course DID come back with bread and wine in hand. Navigating the "family-style" dinner was an awkward challenge for two uncultured twenty-something men (Oh, you put the bread on the plate, not in the bowl. Are we expected to eat all the soup? Will they think it's weird if we eat all the soup? Do we pour the water into the tiny glasses that look more suited for whiskey than water -- or are the water glasses going to come out later?), but we made it through dinner without committing any serious faux pas (or maybe the other guests were merely too polite to laugh at our mistakes). When it came time to pick our entrÃ©e, another warning sign: no prices. This is when we began to debate what our fates would be when the bill did finally find its way to our table. $40 sounds cheap... Is $80 too expensive? Are they going to charge us more now that they've heard us say we would be willing to believe the meal cost $100? We ordered the fried chicken and lamb steak with bated breath. When she brought us our last course -- daringly rich ice cream -- and that oh-so-sinister piece of paper, the moment of truth was at hand. $45 for two people. How entirely reasonable! How utterly inexpensive for this veritable feast of delectable delights! Needless to say we left with a new-found respect for the culinary talents of this small Californian hamlet and a deep gratitude that we would in fact NOT be selling our cars and taking on second jobs upon our return home. Highly recommended.</text><Response>None< /Response><Pics>None< /Pics>< username>
Robin O'Connell< /username>

<gmap_id>0x808fc6d1e2deb8ab:0x315dd6ab2d2ec9b0< /gmap_id><Rate>5<//Rate>< name>
Igor Chentsov</name>
<resp>None<//resp>< Review>
Service is good, this is family owned store - owner and his wife are very friendly. Prices are a bit lower than "European food & liquor", assortment is decent (you won't find variety of fresh cooked food like russian salads, but everything else is present).  They have hot/cold smoked fish, russian sausages, variety of frozen foods like pelmeni, russian cultets, potato cutlets (zrazy), and a big assortment of russian/ukranian chocolate candies. No hard liquor, but owner said he is getting license to sell beer/wine. What else... parking may be scarce because of some museum located nearby, but store got reserved parking spot recently so it wont be a big issue.< /Review>

< userid>
115004911316610456822< /userid>
<pictures>None<//pictures>< text>
My family & I live nearby & usually have excellent service. 3 visits ago an employee suggested the new "Ultimate" Spicy Italian. Had an excellent taste with a garlic spread & special cheese melted onto the bread.

2 visits ago a gentleman who they say his name is Hustler provided horrible customer service. I asked for a new sandwich advertised & he flat out told me he didn't know how to make it. So I had to choose something else. He seemed to have a bad attitude period. I thought perhaps a one - off.  I decide to get a wrap. He says just so you know on wraps we only give you half the meat like a 6 inch. I respond on your menu it says you get footlong portion in a wrap. Is that incorrect? He says he doesn't know & that all he knows is you can't close wrap with footlong worth of meat. So I still order it & just let him be.

Fast forward to tonight. "Hustler" is working yet again. The gentleman ordering a sandwich in front of me & my 2 boys gets into it with Hustler saying I got this today at a Subway for lunch. Hustler states they are different & seems to have attitude. He takes order for my 1st son, then Audrey starts making sandwich for 2nd son. He asks if I'm getting a sandwich & I tell him I am still debating. Then when I ask for a bread listed on chart, he states they have every bread except that one they don't carry. So I choose another...& he says he doesn't know what that is. So I select a 3rd bread & he makes my sandwich. Another guest enters the store. While Audrey rings up the sandwiches she is engaging with my boys & I and is making conversation being friendly & jokes that she didn't make my sandwich with love as she did the other two. I joke back that I missed out. She says she will put a smiley face on mine as well. So all of us share a laugh waiting for my card to process. All of a sudden, Hustler yells loudly, 'can you all be quiet, I cannot hear my customer!" Very loud & rudely. We are all in shock. Even Audrey softy responds something like ok Hustler, now it is awkward. As we leave, I say to the guest who is waiting for her food, I apologize ma'am if we were too loud & she says gesturing, waving & shaking head, 'oh no you all are fine.' I told Audrey I was still going to give her a 5 star review despite the antics of her co-worker.

I am a VP of Sales for a multi million dollar Company, we were not loud & I've managed 100's of store, District Manages, Store Managers etc. & his behavior is one of the worst I've seen now on multiple occasions. I will still leave my 5 star review for all of the other employees I have encountered like Audrey. However, 'Hustler' needs some serious Coaching or perhaps should not be in a customer service position period.

Any questions or concerns, please reach out to me.</text>

< name>
Kandy Gentry<//name>
<time>1610121633775< /time><Rate>5</Rate>< Review>
There's a reason this Habit doesn't have 5 stars.  Every time I eat here I have a bad experience.  A few months back, my son asked for more ketchup and the girl who works there, scooped up about 30 packets, slammed them on his tray and walked away.  Half the packets fell off of his tray  and onto the floor. It was quite the scene.  During another visit, I forgot to put my mask on when I entered the restaurant and an employee told me to put it on.  I apologized and quickly took the mask out of my pocket to put it on.  The employee said, "a lot of good it does there". Today was the last straw.  Not only did I order 45 min in advance and end of waiting curbside for a long time but the employee who brought out the food had an attitude, gave me a dirty look and said something under her breath. To add insult to injury, the fries were lukewarm and soggy. The burgers were cold, the buns were squashed and they hardly had any lettuce in them. On top of that, I ordered online and they also got the order wrong.  You can tell the order was rushed.  That was my very last visit.  After many years of being a loyal customer, I will no longer be eating at the Habit.  I'll just drive a few more miles out  and go to In n Out.</Review>

<Review>We've been to the Habit Burger 4 or 5 times and the first 2 times in December had long lines, great food, and superior help with clearing tables and asking about service and if they could help you with anything else. The decor is nice and a complete change from the Carls Jr. The last 2 times we've gone there, it's been one thing after another. I took my sons to this "new place" to try it out and the order was messed up and I had to go back and order another drink and fries which should have been a combination but wasn't ordered in that way. The girl that was at the counter when that happened was not at all customer friendly. Today we went there again, and my chicken sandwich was lacking the BBQ sauce that had been ordered. It was so bland, no taste at all. My husband's salad was bland with (very thin) ceasar dressing. We even had to ask to have the table cleared when we got there and it was not busy. Others working there were having some sort of a meeting. No more asking around if you need anything or if everything is ok. I don't think they will last if they don't change back to what they were in the first few weeks. Right now, I don't plan on going back there. Also today the music was terrible. Sounded like somebody's garage band way back. Terrible.</Review>< rate>

Not required, please see below:
The U.S. Patriot Act, which was passed to fight terrorism in 2001, does not mandate that car dealers run a credit check and does not require you to allow a credit check to occur. Car dealers are allowed to pull your credit only if you consent, according to the Fair Credit Reporting Act.

After all my research was done, the Toyota Highlander Hybrid came out on top, and I dug deep to decide on the features I wanted (yep - I like creature comforts coupled with great gas mileage and decided on the Platinum Limited), the price I was willing to pay, and made ready to buy. I called every dealership that had the vehicle with the specs I wanted and gave them every opportunity to earn my business.

One dealership was spot on - except the color. I guess the other dealerships thought I wasn't serious, so when I shared this information with them, they told me they couldn't match the deal.

I called just before 9 PM on Friday evening and spoke with Matt. When I shared the deal I had brokered and the proof, he asked to call me back in a few minutes. I was startled when just a couple of minutes later he called me back and met the deal.

If you are in the market and are considering Toyota, really, you need look no further than Simi Valley Toyota. From the moment I walked in to the moment I drove off, no twinge of regret. < Text>
TL;DR 10/10 would recommend

After weeks of online searching, dealing with unsavory used salespeople, and general exhaustion with the car buying process, I found the car of my dreams! Problem was, it was a bit over budget and too far away for me to drive in to negotiate face-to-face.

The first person I communicated with, Whitney, was -letâ€™s just say- less than helpful. Turns out she is an outside contractor that doesnâ€™t actually work for the dealership (she almost turned me away from going here at all UNTIL....)

By some grace of heaven, Whitney was out of the office when I called one evening and I spoke with the manager, Matt B. He was the opposite of her. He was personable and professional. He was honest about the pricing limitations, but was able to give me an out the door price we could both live with.

At the dealership, the salesperson, Dustin, went out of his way to make me feel comfortable with my car buying decision. Answering my 3469373 questions about the car, explaining everything in the CARFAX as well as letting my go on an extended test drive.

When it came time to sign the papers, there was a small snafu where the office put it the wrong zip code, resulting in a $211 tax bump. Because Matt and I had already agreed on a price, the manager on duty at the time, Marlon, personally came over to apologize for their mistake and agreed to honor the price we had set.

Signing papers took awhile(nothing new there) but the lounge was comfortably with two large televisions and a coffee machine. The finance guy, Ahmed, was there way past closing answering my additional 90486 questions I had about the process. He is also a pretty funny guy.

When I got my keys and got out to my car,
They had washed the car and re-filled the gas tank for me and was sitting pretty waiting for me at the door.

Overall, I would recommend this dealership, especially since they extend their power train warranty to any vehicle purchases at their dealership, regardless it its a Toyota or not.

Thank you all for a positive car buying experience!<//Text>

< Review>
I normally take my car to this dealer for service as it is the original place of which I had purchased it from. My last 3 oil changes had been fine, but this time when I went in for my fourth oil change, everything went not as expected. I waited the usual time frame for the job to be completed and was soon alerted that my oil change service was done.

I quickly got into my car and everything seemed to be running great on my way back home. As soon as I arrive at my house, I started to inspect my vehicle for any issues and when I looked at the front, there was an oil mess on the passenger head lamp and top of the fender. I grab one of my cleaning clothes to wipe it off and before I start to do so, I noticed that there is a deep scrape with missing paint above the head lamp on top of the fender. I quickly became infuriated and decided to do a more thorough inspection and discovered two parallel scratches above the said damage and a nick on the driver side top of the fender.

This is absolutely unacceptable! I am someone who takes great care of my car as I take extreme pride in it and to see this unnecessary damage that wasn't there before I had brought it in really made me feel a lot of hate towards this dealer. When I take my care in for service, I expect the dealer to treat my car with the same care and consideration as I would have towards it. The mechanic that worked on my car was extremely sloppy with their work and it is evident that they had absolutely no regard for my vehicle. This is a horrible representation of this dealer as it portrays their service as being unprofessional, reckless and uncaring.

I will no longer be visiting this dealer for any of my needs after this incident. I am very sad about what happened to my car and honestly was not expecting something like this to happen, especially from Toyota. Perhaps they should invest in better employees that actually care about their work and have respect for the customer's property. My suggestion to anyone thinking of coming here is, don't. If you care about your car as much as I do mine, then consider looking for a much more professional shop to visit otherwise you will run the risk of having your car incur unwanted damage before you leave.< /Review>

The finance manager Seth Hidalgo not only explained every portion of every document I was signing, but also had a great sense of humor and additionally got me a better deal for my extended warranty due to my communicated needs (I am an Uber Driver and he put more maximum miles on my extended service warranty without additional charge to give me extra peace of mind). < Text>
I LOVE JULIAN!
I had the most amazing, honest, no nonsense experience with DCH's TOP sales person Julian. From our very first conversation I could tell that Julian was a listener, which is key in my opinion, to giving me the vehicle I need. He didn't make me feel like he was giving the speech, "I hear what you are saying, but I think this would be better," or "I know your asking for this car, but what if we could work something out..." and try and up sale me on a car I don't want or need.

I asked Julian hard questions that no other dealership would answer over the phone. When he wasn't sure about the answer he told me so, and said that he would find out and call me back. Julian did just as he said he would. He was able to give me most of the information I asked for over the phone, so I didn't have to waste my time driving to another dealership and have another horrible experience. Because of his honestly and hard work, I walked into DCH knowing I was ready to buy a car from Julian. I was able to trust that he would stay on the path I had outlined.

Once at DCH Julian had the two vehicles had asked to look at. He was completely ready with information about the two vehicles. I have never seen any other car sales person be so organized and upfront. And before meeting Julian I had been to most of the dealerships in the San Fernando Valley. Neither Julian or his sales manager tried to pull anything "salesmen like." The entire experience was transparent, and actually, was pretty enjoyable. I drove off in the car of my dreams and Julian is the one who made it happen.

I can't wait to buy another car with Julian and DCH. If you hate buying a vehicle like I did, do yourself a favor and set an appointment with Julian. Buying a car is supposed to be exciting, fun and bring you happiness and with DCH and Julian it finally will be!.< /Text>

COSTCO member and considering Toyota DCH of Simi Valley with COSTCO Auto Program? Think Twice.

After test driving and our interests peaked to purchase selected vehicles, we were unprepared with what seemed to be figures well surpassed what the COSTCO program should have offered us. Plus to our great disappointment, the documents handed to us were not displayed with the COSTCO AUTO PROGRAM logo on top, but instead with fees on top of fees, high interest rates that ended with a total so inflated, you would question COSTCO's reputable Auto Program. "Exclusive" prices for COSTCO members? Not this place. It was especially disheartening when your contact is supposed to work WITH the COSTCO members, not AGAINST and TAKEN ADVANTAGE OF (yeah, we dealt with 2 more salesmen after Karen got our unsatisfied answers). We've learned later from others here in Simi (who are COSTCO members) that they had similar experiences and told us this location should be avoided at all costs.
What makes it more personal for us is we purchased a 06 Toyota Highlander back in 2006 with the COSTCO Auto Program at this location and had such a great experience with them, that we thought, years later, we would have that same experience again. But truth be told, it was a far cry from what we experienced back then.
Either this Simi Toyota COSTCO AP team needs re-training, or restructuring, we will definitely not returning at this location anytime soon for our Toyota purchases.<//Text>< Resp>

<user_id>101957273611070704191< /user_id><username>Jefferson Baker</username><date>1483126826255</date>< rating>

< review>
As someone who tends to hang onto cars well after the 15 year, 150,000 mile mark, and for whom a car is simply a way to get from point A to point B, I was not looking forward to going through the hassle of purchasing a new car.  TrueCar pointed us to DCH Toyota of Simi Valley, and they quoted us a price for a new car that was within $1000 of what we were planning to spend for a used car of the previous year, with 20k miles on it.  We therefore thought it was worth the hour drive to see what they had to offer.  I kept waiting for the other shoe to drop during the whole process, and while there was the obligatory presentation of the various extended bumper to bumper, maintenance, tire and other extended warranties, they accepted whatever decisions we arrived at without pressure.  We now have the car we wanted, and they sold it to us at a price that is technically below what they originally quoted.  Yes, there were the obligatory credit checks, insurance verifications, releases and other papers to sign, time waiting while they prepared the car, "dealer prep", licensing and other unpleasant fees and chores associated with buying a car.  But they made the whole process as painless as possible.  Finally, I want to give a special shout out to Brendan, who guided us through the afternoon to a successful conclusion.</review>

<review>I'm a High School Math Teacher in Simi Valley, CA.  On Aug 31, 2016, my wife and I purchased a brand new 2016 Toyota Rav4 XLE Hybrid from a truly wonderful salesman, Cody Segal.  I would recommend Cody Segal to any friends, colleagues, or students looking to buy a car.  Cody was knowledgeable and really cared about us finding what was right for our needs; we gladly put our trust in Cody, now and in the future.

We began our search several months ago.  My wife and I were planning on buying a 2-3 year old used Toyota with low miles.  We stopped by the Simi Valley Toyota dealership to test drive a Corolla, Camry, and Prius.  While at the dealership, I met the salesman, Cody Segal.  Cody also had us sit in the Rav4, and my wife immediately fell in love with this Crossover SUV...that decision was made, we wanted a Rav4!

At this time, we were still expecting to buy a used Rav4..  But then I started reading online about the Rav4 HYBRID models.  I fell in love with the idea of this gas saving Hybrid, along with Toyota's front-running experience with Hybrids (because of their Prius background).  And since, the 2016 was the first year for the Rav4 to offer a Hybrid, there simply weren't any used ones available!  My wife and I started to consider buying a new vehicle Hybrid instead.

So, we started talking to Cody Segal about the pros and cons of New vs Used, Hybrid vs Gas-only, etc.  Cody was always terrific; he never pressured us to buy one car over another.  Instead, Cody would listen to all my thoughts and concerns, and then give me excellent food for thought in his knowledgeable and always upbeat responses.

As we moved into August, we started to lean towards buying NEW, so we started getting down to business on price negotiations. Since I'm a public school teacher, I registered with my union benefits to be able to receive "Internet" pricing from all the Southern California Toyota dealers (I also registered with AARP deals and something called Edmunds as well...but all these "Internet" pricing deals were basically the same.)  However, when I registered online, suddenly I was overwhelmed with e-mails from lots of Toyota dealerships here in So. Cal.  Typically, I would discuss the deals with Cody at SV Toyota.  He never said a bad word about any of these other dealers; in fact, he often sincerely suggested we take one of the other deals if that would make us happy.

As August unfolded, Toyota's 2016 clearance specials began to surface.  Suddenly, there were rebates and financing options that started to significantly bring the prices down.  Now we were in full negotiation mode, and all that remained was being able to afford it on my single teaching income!   I would call Cody day or night or weekend to fire questions at him, as well as try to negotiate an affordable price.  Cody, at all times, kept up his always-positive-attitude and would always try to accommodate my issues.  Again, note that I was also in contact with several other Toyota dealerships as well...and believe me, they all wanted my business as well!

Finally, on Aug 31, we decided to bite the bullet and buy our new Rav4 Hybrid.  Cody had gotten us a great price for a new White 2016 Rav4 that he had on the Simi Valley lot.  Note that Frontier Toyota had a Blue one I wanted and they agreed to match the price we were offered at the Simi Valley dealership!  But when I discussed it with my wife, she said she would be happy with White, and we both agreed that we wanted to buy our car from Cody Segal in Simi Valley.  After two months of analysis and negotiations, we felt like Cody was almost family to us, and we were thrilled to finally do business with him.

We've now owned the car for less than 1 month.  We love it.  And every time I show my friends the car or tell my students about it, we bring up Cody.  He's the reason we purchased our car from DCH Toyota of Simi Valley, and we would not hesitate to buy other cars from him in the future!
Thanks Cody.  My wife loves our new 2016 Rav4 XLE Hybrid, and Happy Wife = Happy Life.  :)</review><user>112727852509367852745<//user>< response>

<rating>5< /rating><review>We had a great experience buying a Prius C at DCH this weekend. In fact, it was the best car-buying experience we have ever had (we are both in our mid '70s so that is a lot of experience). Cesar Garcia was our sales rep.

We were unsure that the car would be what we really wanted, so he (they) let us take the "unwind" car for an extended test drive (it already had about 300 miles on it from a short-time owner whose credit had fallen through). Then we went home to do some research that evening. We wanted to check on whether the price was really a good deal (it was) and whether getting a 2012 with all of the "bells and whistles" would be better than getting a 2013 with fewer features (it was). So we went back yesterday and bought it!

We had also researched extended warranties and found we could get a better deal through an insurance policy, so we declined the policy they were offering. We declined a few other options, but did opt for the interior/exterior surface protection (sort of like Scotch Guard for the whole car). We want to keep it looking nice!

After the paperwork was done, Cesar helped us sync my phone to the bluetooth system and showed us a lot of the features. <Time>1342400626208< /Time><rating>5</rating>< Review>
We were in the market for an affordable new sedan for my 17 year old daughters first vehicle.  Costco Auto Buying program referred us to Miller Toyota, Culver City, which is 30 miles from our home, and we had an appt set up with a rep at 2pm yesterday.  Our first stop was William L Morris Chevrolet to test drive the Chevy Cruze and Malibu.  Jeff Morris was very concerned about my daughters satisfaction with her first car and the fact that we would have to leave in the mid day heat from Simi Valley to Culver City Toyota, when I stated that he had a very good relationship with Nick Dulea, general manager across the street at DCH Toyota of Simi Valley, and that, if we wish, would make a phone call and have Nick and his team take care of us.  We agreed to do this at least to see and test drive the Camry and possibly avoid the hassle of driving to Culver City to find the same car.  Jeff Morris made the phone call; and we were greeted at DCH Toyota of Simi Valley by general manager, Nick Dulea and rep Tony Fierro, with smiles and handshakes making us feel right at home.  After describing basically what my daughter was looking for, Tony swiftly escorted outside to the lot to look for the camry SE 4 dr White exterior with Black Leather interior minus moonroof and navigation. Nick from the very moment we arrived assured us with confidence that the price and auto would meet or exceed our expectations....and he was correct.  Once we narrowed down the specific features of the auto; Nick dealer located the exact vehicle at Northridge Toyota; dealer traded the vehicle in the 1 hour timeframe it took us to have lunch and return to dealership.  After lunch, Tony returned with the car; had us inspect to make sure it was indeed the exact auto we desired with all included features, meanwhile Nick kept showing us the features and made double and triple sure all features were just as we desired so that he could meet our needs of finding the exact car with the exact features Nikki desired.  After verification that the dealer traded Camry was exactly as we desired, the car was sent for detailing and we proceeded with the paperwork process and financial.  All the team members were VERY kind and compassionate and congratulatory at every step.  Overall, the entire customer experience, which lasted a total of 4 hours, was worth the time effort and persistence and easily among the best we have had (10/10).  Nick assured a better than Costco price, delivered on his promise, made us feel at ease without pressure or coercion, and due to the huge savings, we were able to afford some essentials, like LoJack System, Door Guard safety package, protective 3M rear window tint package, AND most importantly, 7 year 75 Mile extended Platinum Care Coverage. One of the salient selling features of this car was the 10 airbag and 5 star safety rating as well as many many years of customer loyalty record sales and the fact that we were recent purchasers of a 2011 Toyota Sienna Minivan.  Cheers to DCH Simi Valley Toyota - Nick D, gen mgr, and his entire support team, for making my daughters FIRST auto experience painless and extraordinary.  God Bless DCH, and all the future and past happy purchasers as well as Jeff Morris at William L Morris Chevrolet for thinking beyond the almighty "sale" to truly satisfy the customer !!!<//Review>

<name>Andrew Set< /name><Date>1330546951419<//Date><Rate>5< /Rate>< Review>
I was looking for a Prius and this dealership is the closest one from where I live so it was my first option to get the Prius from. I contacted total of 4 dealerships, it became a competition between DCH Simi Valley and Thousand Oaks Toyota. After about 2 weeks of negotiation, DCH won my business.

I was helped by Dennis Piechowski and he was very helpful. The first time we spoke on the phone, he's not like regular sales persons who over acting and try to be your best friend. But when I met him, he's actually very friendly and very knowledgeable about Prius because he actually owned one. He helped me through all the buying process, went back and forward to the finance department to get me the best deal I wanted. The whole process took about 3-4 hrs, from test drive till I got the keys. He also picked me up him self, to get my Camry which was due for an oil change at the dealership.

I got a free bluetooth which was installed in the 2nd week after purchase, no problem with that. I was told the installation takes about 1-3hrs, it was actually completed in less than an hour. The Prius was also missing the hooks for the carpet floor mat for the driver seat, but Dennis took care of that, no complaints.

Compare to Hamer Toyota (where I bought my very first new car from, a Camry 2011), DCH is a winner in all aspects. Trust me, don't go to Hamer Toyota, they suck!< /Review>
